      "message": "The results below compare the cases with and without BOOST_ASIO_DISABLE_EPOLL\nenabled.\n\nio_uring + epoll (BOOST_ASIO_DISABLE_EPOLL removed):\n```\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d io_uring + epoll (window\u003d60s) Wed Jun 10 02:49:08 UTC 2026 \u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\n\n--- sensor instance counts ---\n  HwmonTempSensor        1001\n  ADCSensor              17\n\n--- daemon wchan / syscall ---\n  hwmontempsensor        pid\u003d412    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003drunning\n  psusensor              pid\u003d416    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  adcsensor              pid\u003d407    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  fansensor              pid\u003d411    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  ipmbsensor             pid\u003d414    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  mcutempsensor          pid\u003d415    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  intelcpusensor         pid\u003d445    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  entity-manager         pid\u003d318    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  swampd                 pid\u003d440    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  phosphor-regulators    pid\u003d273    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  bmcweb                 pid\u003d245    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  pldmd                  pid\u003d478    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  mctpd                  pid\u003d253    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  (syscall: epoll_wait\u003d232/252, io_uring_enter\u003d426/427 depending on arch)\n\n--- cpufreq state ---\n  cpufreq scaling not exposed (likely fixed-frequency BMC)\n\n--- /proc/stat cpu deltas (60s) ---\n  before: cpu  4516 0 5098 4811 187 0 2 0 0 0\n  after : cpu  4965 0 5703 15324 187 0 2 0 0 0\n  per second: user\u003d7.5 sys\u003d10.1 idle\u003d175.2 iowait\u003d0.0 irq\u003d0.0 softirq\u003d0.0\n\n  intr/s : 13044\n  ctxt/s : 4566\n\n--- I2C IRQ deltas ---\n  IRQ 52:  aspeed_vhub               +34 total over 60s (1/s)\n  IRQ 59:  1e78a480.i2c              +599380 total over 60s (9990/s)\n\n--- D-Bus PropertiesChanged on /sensors (60s window) ---\n  signals on /sensors: 745  (12/s)\n  all PropertiesChanged: 926  (15/s)\n\n--- hwmontempsensor pid\u003d412 ---\nVmSize:    18484 kB\nVmRSS:     16864 kB\nThreads:        1\n  wchan  : aspeed_i2c_master_xfer\n  syscall: 426 0x9 0x1a 0x0 0x0 0x0 0x8 0x7edd09a8 0x76b25110\n  anon fds:\n    anon_inode:[eventfd]\n    anon_inode:[eventpoll]\n    anon_inode:[io_uring]\n    anon_inode:[pidfd]\n    anon_inode:[timerfd]\n  io_uring fdinfo (fd 9):\n    pos:        0\n    flags:      02000002\n    mnt_id:     14\n    ino:        6759\n\n--- sensor value sanity (first 5 HwmonTempSensor paths) ---\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp \u003d d 28.875\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_1 \u003d d 28.875\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_10 \u003d d 28.875\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_100 \u003d d 28.875\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_101 \u003d d 28.875\n\n--- D-Bus get-property latency (50 probes) ---\n  path: /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp\n  microseconds: count\u003d50 min\u003d20000 avg\u003d30400 p50\u003d30000 p90\u003d40000 p99\u003d40000 max\u003d40000\n\n--- top snapshot ---\nMem: 230548K used, 729152K free, 12036K shrd, 0K buff, 93332K cached\nCPU:   4% usr   9% sys   0% nic  85% idle   0% io   0% irq   0% sirq\nLoad average: 1.37 0.96 0.39 3/160 2620\n  PID  PPID USER     STAT   VSZ %VSZ CPU %CPU COMMAND\n  412     1 root     R    18484   2%   1   5% /usr/libexec/dbus-sensors/hwmontempsensor\n 2619   494 root     R     2860   0%   0   5% top -bn1\n  318     1 root     S    37688   4%   0   0% /usr/libexec/entity-manager/entity-manager\n  334     1 root     S    33348   3%   1   0% /usr/sbin/rsyslogd -n -iNONE\n\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d END io_uring + epoll \u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\n\n```\n\nio_uring only (BOOST_ASIO_DISABLE_EPOLL existed):\n```\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d io_uring only (window\u003d60s) Wed Jun 10 02:22:27 UTC 2026 \u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\n\n--- sensor instance counts ---\n  HwmonTempSensor        1001\n  ADCSensor              17\n\n--- daemon wchan / syscall ---\n  hwmontempsensor        pid\u003d412    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  psusensor              pid\u003d416    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  adcsensor              pid\u003d407    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  fansensor              pid\u003d411    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  ipmbsensor             pid\u003d414    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  mcutempsensor          pid\u003d415    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  intelcpusensor         pid\u003d444    wchan\u003dio_cqring_wait       syscall\u003d426\n  entity-manager         pid\u003d323    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  swampd                 pid\u003d441    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  phosphor-regulators    pid\u003d268    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  bmcweb                 pid\u003d336    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  pldmd                  pid\u003d488    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  mctpd                  pid\u003d247    wchan\u003ddo_epoll_wait        syscall\u003d252\n  (syscall: epoll_wait\u003d232/252, io_uring_enter\u003d426/427 depending on arch)\n\n--- cpufreq state ---\n  cpufreq scaling not exposed (likely fixed-frequency BMC)\n\n--- /proc/stat cpu deltas (60s) ---\n  before: cpu  10443 0 11536 2247 82764 0 7 0 0 0\n  after : cpu  10916 0 12030 2247 93351 0 7 0 0 0\n  per second: user\u003d7.9 sys\u003d8.2 idle\u003d0.0 iowait\u003d176.4 irq\u003d0.0 softirq\u003d0.0\n\n  intr/s : 11440\n  ctxt/s : 4501\n\n--- I2C IRQ deltas ---\n  IRQ 51:  aspeed_vhub               +29 total over 60s (0/s)\n  IRQ 58:  1e78a480.i2c              +598200 total over 60s (9970/s)\n\n--- D-Bus PropertiesChanged on /sensors (60s window) ---\n  signals on /sensors: 3037  (50/s)\n  all PropertiesChanged: 3221  (53/s)\n\n--- hwmontempsensor pid\u003d412 ---\nVmSize:    18472 kB\nVmRSS:     16792 kB\nThreads:        1\n  wchan  : io_cqring_wait\n  syscall: running\n  anon fds:\n    anon_inode:[io_uring]\n    anon_inode:[pidfd]\n  io_uring fdinfo (fd 5):\n    pos:        0\n    flags:      02000002\n    mnt_id:     14\n    ino:        6354\n    SqMask:     0x3fff\n    SqHead:     1403344\n    SqTail:     1403344\n    CachedSqHead:       1403344\n    CqMask:     0x7fff\n    CqHead:     1403342\n    CqTail:     1403342\n    CachedCqTail:       1403342\n\n--- sensor value sanity (first 5 HwmonTempSensor paths) ---\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp \u003d d 28.75\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_1 \u003d d 28.75\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_10 \u003d d 28.75\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_100 \u003d d 28.75\n  /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp_101 \u003d d 28.75\n\n--- D-Bus get-property latency (50 probes) ---\n  path: /xyz/openbmc_project/sensors/temperature/Board_Temp\n  microseconds: count\u003d50 min\u003d20000 avg\u003d29200 p50\u003d30000 p90\u003d40000 p99\u003d40000 max\u003d40000\n\n--- top snapshot ---\nMem: 253948K used, 705752K free, 13700K shrd, 0K buff, 94940K cached\nCPU:   0% usr   9% sys   0% nic   0% idle  90% io   0% irq   0% sirq\nLoad average: 0.64 0.67 0.46 1/153 4191\n  PID  PPID USER     STAT   VSZ %VSZ CPU %CPU COMMAND\n  412     1 root     S    18472   2%   0   5% /usr/libexec/dbus-sensors/hwmontempsensor\n 4190  2961 root     R     2860   0%   1   5% top -bn1\n  442     1 root     S    41284   4%   0   0% /usr/sbin/rsyslogd -n -iNONE\n  323     1 root     S    37688   4%   1   0% /usr/libexec/entity-manager/entity-manager\n\n\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d END io_uring only \u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\u003d\n```\n\nSummary:\n```\nReal-hardware measurement on dual-core AST2600 BMC under heavy sensor reading load.\n1018 sensor instances (1001 HwmonTempSensor + 17 ADCSensor).\n60 s sample window per snapshot.\nKernel version v6.18.33\n\n                                upstream             patched\n                                (DISABLE_EPOLL on)   (no DISABLE_EPOLL)\n                                ------------------   ------------------\n    iowait per second           176.4 ticks          0\n    idle per second             0 (frozen)           175.2 ticks\n\n    user ticks/s                7.9                  7.5\n    sys ticks/s                 8.2                  10.1\n    user+sys combined           16.1                 17.6        (≈ same)\n    ctxt rate                   4501 /s              4566 /s     (≈ same)\n    intr rate                   11440/s              13044/s     (≈ same)\n\n    i2c bus IRQ rate            9970 /s              9990 /s     (within 0.2 %)\n\n    D-Bus get-property latency  count\u003d50             count\u003d50\n                                min\u003d20000 us         min\u003d20000 us\n                                avg\u003d29200 us         avg\u003d30400 us\n                                p50\u003d30000 us         p50\u003d30000 us\n                                p90\u003d40000 us         p90\u003d40000 us\n                                p99\u003d40000 us         p99\u003d40000 us\n                                max\u003d40000 us         max\u003d40000 us\n                                (identical distribution)\n\n    PropertiesChanged signals   50 /s on /sensors    12 /s on /sensors\n    on /sensors                 (window-noise — see below)\n\n    sensor value sanity         28.75 °C             28.875 °C   (1 quant step\n                                                                  between samples)\n\n    hwmon STAT                  D (TASK_UNINT)       R\n    hwmon VmRSS                 16.8 MB              16.9 MB\n    mem used                    254 MB               230 MB\n\n    cpufreq scaling             not exposed          not exposed\n\n    hwmon wchan                 io_cqring_wait       do_epoll_wait\n    hwmon syscall               426 (io_uring_enter) 252 (epoll_wait)\n    anon fds                    io_uring, pidfd      eventpoll, timerfd,\n                                                     eventfd, io_uring,\n                                                     pidfd\n```\n\ni2c bus IRQ rate 9970 vs 9990 /s (within 0.2 %) — same sensor reads at the same\ncadence. busctl get-property latency distributions essentially identical: avg\n29200 vs 30400 us, p50 30000 us both, p90/p99 40000 us both.\n\nctxt rate 4501 vs 4566 /s. user+sys CPU 16.1 vs 17.6 ticks/s (~10 %, probably\nwithin noise on a 60 s window).\n\niowait flips: 176.4 ticks/s → 0; idle resumes from 0 (frozen) to 175.2 /s. hwmon\nSTAT D → R. ~22 MB lower RSS on patched.\n\nSensor reads remain functional in both configs (1001 HwmonTempSensor instances\nreturning ~28.8 °C).\n\nPropertiesChanged signal rate varies between the two samples (50/s vs 12/s on\n/sensors) but this reflects underlying sensor-value oscillation in different\nsample windows, not the patch — i2c read rate is identical.\n\nNo measurable regression in latency, throughput, or sensor functionality.\niowait/load metrics now reflect actual system state.\n\nThat said, I still don\u0027t think these results can be generalized across all system\nconfigurations, so my opinion remains that we should validate this on a wider\nvariety of platforms. However, based on these results, I don\u0027t see any\nsignificant performance difference or regression between using io_uring and\nio_uring + epoll.\n\nIn fact, I think the io_uring + epoll approach makes more sense if we want to\navoid exposing potentially misleading idle and iowait numbers. This becomes even\nmore important in rack-scale deployments where the BMC itself is monitored by a\ncentral monitoring system. In those environments, it\u0027s better to avoid creating\nunnecessary confusion from metrics that can be easily misinterpreted.\n\nThanks!\n\nJae",
